b'[<p><i><b>UFC 60: Hughes vs. Gracie</b></i> was a <a href="/wiki/Mixed_martial_arts" title="Mixed martial arts">mixed martial arts</a> event held by the <a href="/wiki/Ultimate_Fighting_Championship" title="Ultimate Fighting Championship">Ultimate Fighting Championship</a> on May 27, 2006.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup>  The event took place at the <a href="/wiki/Staples_Center" title="Staples Center">Staples Center</a>, in <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Los_Angeles,_California" title="Los Angeles, California">Los Angeles, California</a> and was broadcast live on <a href="/wiki/Pay-per-view" title="Pay-per-view">pay-per-view</a> in the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> and <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canada</a>.\n</p>, <p>Headlining the card was a non-title <a href="/wiki/Catchweight" title="Catchweight">catchweight</a> (175 lb) match between then-current <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/UFC_Welterweight_Championship" title="UFC Welterweight Championship">UFC Welterweight Champion</a> <a href="/wiki/Matt_Hughes_(fighter)" title="Matt Hughes (fighter)">Matt Hughes</a>, and <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/UFC_hall_of_fame" title="UFC hall of fame">UFC Hall of Famer</a> <a href="/wiki/Royce_Gracie" title="Royce Gracie">Royce Gracie</a>, the winner of <i><a href="/wiki/UFC_1" title="UFC 1">UFC 1</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/UFC_2" title="UFC 2">UFC 2</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/UFC_4" title="UFC 4">UFC 4</a></i>. This was Gracie\'s first match in the <a href="/wiki/Ultimate_Fighting_Championship" title="Ultimate Fighting Championship">UFC</a> and in the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> since <i><a href="/wiki/UFC_5" title="UFC 5">UFC 5</a></i>.\n</p>, <p>The event drew 620,000  buys, becoming the best-selling <a href="/wiki/Pay-per-view" title="Pay-per-view">pay-per-view</a> in <a href="/wiki/Ultimate_Fighting_Championship" title="Ultimate Fighting Championship">UFC</a> history up to that point, and the first to break the $20 million mark in gross PPV sales.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-3"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup>\n</p>]'